    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1953-02-13T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1953-02-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="285"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d285">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">886A.2553/2–1353</note>
                <head>No. 285<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Conversation, by the Officer in Charge of
                        Lebanon—Syria—Iraq Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_FR1"
                        >Funkhouser</persName>) and the Chief of the Petroleum Policy
                            Staff(<persName corresp="#p_ERH1">Eakens</persName>)</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian"
                            type="conversation-or-meeting-date" when="1953-02-13">February 13,
                            1953</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>Subject:</head>
                    <item>Proposed Treasury Action re Auditing <gloss target="#t_Aramco1"
                            >Aramco</gloss> Tax Statements</item>
                </list>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>Participants:</head>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_PED1">PED</gloss>–Mr. <persName corresp="#p_ERH1"
                            >Eakens</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_LE1">L/E</gloss>–Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MSD1"
                            >Metzger</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_ARA1">ARA</gloss>–Mr. <persName corresp="#p_DMB1"
                            >Davis</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_OSA1">OSA</gloss>–Mr. Bernbaum</item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_NE1">NE</gloss>/<gloss target="#t_E1">E</gloss>–Mr.
                            <persName corresp="#p_BF1">Boardman</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_NE1">NE</gloss>–Mr. <persName corresp="#p_FAD1"
                            >Fritzlan</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_NE1">NE</gloss>–Mr. <persName corresp="#p_FR1"
                            >Funkhouser</persName>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>At a meeting on this subject this afternoon, the following conclusions were
                    reached: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>Change in existing policy of allowing U.S. tax credits for foreign
                            taxes paid by American corporations could have serious economic and
                            political repercussions on U.S. foreign affairs. Such a change might
                            seriously affect not only the relations of oil companies with
                            concessionary countries and the stability of their concessions but also
                            U.S. foreign investment generally.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>The information available regarding Treasury consideration of this
                            problem is meager and the first move should be to find out from Treasury
                            the facts of the case.</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>It was the consensus of the group that the Department should contact
                            the appropriate official in Treasury to express the Department’s
                            interest in this problem and to request whatever facts Treasury can make
                            available. Such an approach might be made on the general basis that “the
                            Department understands that <gloss target="#t_Aramco1">Aramco</gloss>’s
                            1950 tax return has now come up for final audit”. It was considered that
                            at this point an <hi rend="italic">informal</hi> approach would be
                            desirable. It was felt that the approach might most appropriately be
                            made to Mr. <persName>Andrew Overby</persName>, Assistant Secretary of
                            Treasury, by Mr. <persName corresp="#p_LHF1">Linder</persName>.</item>
                        <label>4.</label>
                        <item>Papers prepared by Mr. <persName corresp="#p_BHA1">Byroade</persName>
                            <note n="1" xml:id="d285fn1">Memorandum of Feb. 11, <ref target="#d284">
                                    <hi rend="italic">supra</hi>
                                </ref>.</note> and Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MSD1"
                                >Metzger</persName>
                            <note n="2" xml:id="d285fn2">The paper under reference here is the
                                memorandum by <persName corresp="#p_PH1">Phleger</persName> cited in
                                    <ref target="#d284fn2">footnote 2, <hi rend="italic"
                                    >supra</hi>,</ref> which was drafted by <persName
                                    corresp="#p_MSD1">Metzger</persName>.</note> on this subject are
                            attached.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
